  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "961225db",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"takeaway\">The prompt is translated into genre, mood, theme, and story signals before the titles are ranked.</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.notes}\n",
    "This example uses the newer prompt-based recommender. The user asks for a tense zombie survival horror movie. REC received the highest score at 94.1 percent, followed by The Walking Dead at 93.6 percent. The remaining results also match horror, danger, infection, and survival. This shows that the system can work from a natural-language request instead of requiring the user to enter an existing title.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## What works, and what is still missing?\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"48%\"}\n",
    "<div class=\"status-card good\">\n",
    "<div class=\"eyebrow\">WORKING NOW</div>\n",
    "<h3>The prototype can...</h3>\n",
    "<ul>\n",
    "<li>recommend from a mood or written request</li>\n",
    "<li>find titles similar to a chosen title</li>\n",
    "<li>rank all 7,848 titles</li>\n",
    "<li>show why different signals affected the order</li>\n",
    "</ul>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"48%\"}\n",
    "<div class=\"status-card caution\">\n",
    "<div class=\"eyebrow\">STILL MISSING</div>\n",
    "<h3>I have not yet...</h3>\n",
    "<ul>\n",
    "<li>tested it with a group of real users</li>\n",
    "<li>measured whether users are more satisfied</li>\n",
    "<li>added titles released after 2023</li>\n",
    "<li>finished reviewing every automatic topic label</li>\n",
    "</ul>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.notes}\n",
    "The prototype is working: it can accept different kinds of input and rank the full dataset. But I want to be honest about what I have not proven. I have not tested it with a group of users, so I cannot yet say that it is better than another recommender. Also, the dataset ends in 2023, so newer releases are missing.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Reflection\n",
    "\n",
    ":::: {.columns}\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"32%\"}\n",
    "<div class=\"reflection-card easy\">\n",
    "<div class=\"icon\">✓</div>\n",
    "<h3>What felt easier</h3>\n",
    "<p>Building the first rule-based version and calculating scores.</p>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"32%\"}\n",
    "<div class=\"reflection-card hard\">\n",
    "<div class=\"icon\">!</div>\n",
    "<h3>What was difficult</h3>\n",
    "<p>Finding wrong descriptions and replacing them without mixing up titles.</p>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::: {.column width=\"32%\"}\n",
    "<div class=\"reflection-card learned\">\n",
    "<div class=\"icon\">↗</div>\n",
    "<h3>What I learned</h3>\n",
    "<p>Clean and trustworthy data can matter more than using a complicated model.</p>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "::::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.notes}\n",
    "The first scoring system was fairly straightforward. The most difficult part was the data quality. I had to be careful not to replace a bad description with another wrong one. The biggest lesson for me was that a complicated model cannot fix unreliable data. Cleaning and checking the dataset made the later work much more meaningful.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## What I would do next\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"roadmap simple-roadmap\">\n",
    "<div><span>1</span><b>Test with users</b><p>Ask people whether the top five results match their request.</p></div>\n",
    "<div><span>2</span><b>Improve accuracy</b><p>Tune the scoring and improve prediction scores for harder titles.</p></div>\n",
    "<div><span>3</span><b>Add feedback</b><p>Let users like, dislike, or hide recommendations.</p></div>\n",
    "<div><span>4</span><b>Build the app</b><p>Connect the model to a simple and friendly interface.</p></div>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"priority-box\"><span>MY FIRST PRIORITY</span><strong>Test the recommendations with real people before making the model more complicated.</strong></div>\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.notes}\n",
    "My first next step would be user testing. I would also work on improving prediction accuracy, especially for titles that currently receive lower match scores. I can do that by tuning the scoring weights, improving the mood labels, and using user feedback. After that, I would add newer titles and connect the recommender to a simple interface.\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "## Thank you\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.closing}\n",
    "<div class=\"eyebrow\">THE MAIN IDEA</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "### Choose by how you want to <span class=\"accent\">feel</span>,<br>not only by what genre you know.\n",
    "\n",
    "<p>A cleaner dataset · a more natural search · a shorter watchlist</p>\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"closing-question\">Questions?</div>\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.notes}\n",
    "To finish, the main idea is simple: people do not always know which title or genre they want, but they often know what kind of experience they want. My project uses that feeling as the starting point. Thank you, and I am happy to answer questions.\n",
    ":::"
   ]
  }
